Multi-species Occupancy Models (MSOM)

  • Model occupancy probability of multiple species simultaneously
  • Infer patterns of dependence between species
  • All while accounting for imperfect detection

What can we Learn from MSOMs?

  • Test for dependence between species
  • Do species interactions vary along a gradient?
  • Marginal occupancy probability
  • Conditional occupancy
  • Is occurrence more strongly driven by environmental gradients or interspecific interactions?

Different Flavors of MSOMs

Todays webinar is focused on techniques described by Rota et al.2016.

Technical Details: Natural Parameters

Technical Details: Natural Parameters

Let \(S\) represent the number of species

  • \(S\) \(1^{st}\) order natural parameters
  • \({S \choose 2}\) \(2^{nd}\) order natural parameters
  • Up to \(2^S-1\) natural parameters of maximum order \(S\)

Example: let \(S = 3\):

  • \({3 \choose 1} = 3\) \(1^{st}\) order natural parameters
  • \({3 \choose 2} = 3\) \(2^{nd}\) order natural parameters
  • \({3 \choose 3} = 1\) \(3^{rd}\) order natural parameters
  • \(2 ^ 3 - 1 = 7\) total natural parameters

I only incorporate \(1^{st}\) and \(2^{nd}\) order natural parameters for this talk.

Technical Details: Marginal Occupancy

  • Common method for interpreting occupancy probability
  • Averages over presence / absence of all other species
  • Complex function of natural parameters
    • i.e., not directly obtained from model output
  • Functions for implementation in unmarked
  • Mathematical details in Rota et al.2016

Technical Details: Conditional Occupancy

  • Method for evaluating occupancy of one species when other species are present / absent
  • In specific cases, can be directly obtained from model output
    • Log odds occupancy of each species, conditional on absence of all others
  • In other cases, a complex function of natural parameters
  • Functions for implementation in unmarked
  • Mathematical details in Rota et al.2016

Basic Sampling Procedure

Same general procedure for single-species occupancy models:

  • survey for S species at N sites selected from a population of interest
  • at each site i, conduct \(J_i\) replicate surveys
  • for each species s, during replicate survey j at site i, record detection (\(y_{sij} = 1\)) or non-detection (\(y_{sij} = 0\))
  • record detection-level covariates during each replicate detection / non-detection survey
  • record site-level covariates at each site i

Impelementation in unmarked

  • Incorporated into unmarked by Dr.Ken Kellner
  • Similar syntax to other models implemented in unmarked

Lets first review our example data set and then format for analysis in unmarked.

Data

  • Data from 1437 camera traps placed across 6 states in the mid-Atlantic region, USA
  • Distilled to Coyote, Bobcat, and Red Fox
  • Cameras deployed 3 weeks
  • 1-week replicate sampling period
    • Species recorded as detected if observed at least once during each 1-week sampling period
  • Site-level occupancy covariates, observation-level detection covariates
  • Details in Kays et al.2016

Data

Site-level covariate descriptions:

  • Dist_5km: Proportion disturbance within 5km
  • HDens_5km: Housing density within 5km
  • Latitude / Longitude: Latitude and longitude
  • People_site: Total people recorded / 1000
  • Trail: binary indicator of whether camera was on trail (1) or not (0)

Loading the unmarked package

Load the unmarked package

library(unmarked)

  • Downloading the latest version from GitHub will allow you to fit penalized likelihood models (available on CRAN soon)

Formatting Data

Formatting

Place detection / non-detection data into a named list.

  • each element of the list must be a matrix
y_list <- list(bobcat = as.matrix(bob),
               coyote = as.matrix(coy),
               redfox = as.matrix(fox))

Place detection covariates into a named list.

  • each element of the list must be of the same dimension as each detection / non-detection matrix
det_list <- list(temp = det_covs)

Combine data into an unmarkedFrameOccuMulti object:

msom_data <- unmarkedFrameOccuMulti(y = y_list,
                                    siteCovs = occ_covs,
                                    obsCovs = det_list)

Intercept-only model, assuming independence

Syntax similar to other models in unmarked

  • 1 detection formula for each species
  • 1 occupancy formula for each natural parameter included in model
  • formulas specified as character vector
  • order of formulas follows detection / non-detection list

Fit a model

For now, we assume independence among species. We do this by only allowing \(1^{st}\) order natural parameters (maxOrder = 1).

fit_1 <- occuMulti(detformulas = c('~1', '~1', '~1'),
                   stateformulas = c('~1', '~1', '~1'),
                   maxOrder = 1,
                   data = msom_data)

Intercept-only model, assuming independence

This is equivalent to fitting 3 single-species occupancy models

Intercept-only model, assuming dependence

  • Set maxOrder = 2 to estimate up to \(2^{nd}\) order natural parameters
  • Permits dependence between species
  • Fixes all natural parameters > maxOrder at 0
fit_2 <- occuMulti(detformulas = c('~1', '~1', '~1'),
                   stateformulas = c('~1', '~1', '~1',
                                     '~1', '~1', '~1'),
                   maxOrder = 2,
                   data = msom_data)

Incorporating covariates

  • Any parameter can be modeled as a function of covariates
  • Covariate models for each parameter can be unique
  • Names of detection covariates correspond to names provided in named list
  • Names of occupancy covariates correspond to names in data.frame

The model below is driven less by biology and more by an interest in demonstrating that each parameter can be modeled uniquely.

fit_3 <- occuMulti(detformulas = c('~temp', '~1', '~1'),
                   stateformulas = c('~Dist_5km', '~HDens_5km', '~People_site',
                                     '~Latitude', '~1', '~1'),
                   maxOrder = 2,
                   data = msom_data)

Sample interpretations:

  • For every 1-unit increase disturbance within 5km, the log odds of bobcat occurrence, when coyote and red fox are absent, declines by 22.96
  • When latitude = 0, bobcats are more likely to occur at a site when coyotes are present (and vice versa, \(p < 0.01\))
  • For every 1 unit increase in Latitude, the log odds bobcats will occur at a site decreases by 18.98 if coyotes are also present, relative to equivalent sites where coyotes are absent
    • i.e., as we move north, bobcats are coyotes are less likely to occupy the same site
  • For every 1-unit increase in temperature, the log odds of bobcat detection decreases by 0.31

Conditional occupancy probability

Calculation of conditional and marginal occupancy probabilities is done with the predict function.

  • Create a data.frame for predictions
    • The procedure is equivalent to creating data frames for all other applications of predict
  • Include complete range of observed latitude; hold all other variables at their mean
nd_cond <- data.frame(
  Dist_5km = rep(mean(occ_covs$Dist_5km), 100),
  HDens_5km = rep(mean(occ_covs$HDens_5km), 100),
  People_site = rep(mean(occ_covs$People_site), 100),
  Latitude = seq(min(occ_covs$Latitude), max(occ_covs$Latitude),
                 length.out = 100)
)

Conditional occupancy probability

Predicting bobcat occurrence when coyotes are present

  • species indicates which species we assume when predicting occupancy
  • cond indicates which species we are assuming is present or absent
bob_coy_1 <- predict(fit_3, type = 'state', species = 'bobcat',
                     cond = 'coyote', newdata = nd_cond)
## Bootstrapping confidence intervals with 100 samples

Predicting bobcat occurrence when coyotes are absent

  • putting a - in front of coyote tells predict you wish to assume coyotes are absent
bob_coy_0 <- predict(fit_3, type = 'state', species = 'bobcat',
                     cond = '-coyote', newdata = nd_cond)
## Bootstrapping confidence intervals with 100 samples

Conditional occupancy probability

Formatting data for plotting in ggplot. I skip details, though this procedure is standard for plotting with ggplot.

gg_df_cond <- data.frame(
  latitude = rep(nd_cond$Latitude, 2),
  occupancy = c(bob_coy_1$Predicted,
                bob_coy_0$Predicted),
  low = c(bob_coy_1$lower,
          bob_coy_0$lower),
  high = c(bob_coy_1$upper,
           bob_coy_0$upper),
  conditional = rep(c('Coyote present', 'Coyote absent'),
                    each = 100)
)

Creating a line plot, with ribbons representing limits of 95% confidence intervals. This is standard ggplot2 code.

library(ggplot2)

cond_fig <- ggplot(gg_df_cond, aes(x = latitude, y = occupancy,
                                   group = conditional)) +
  geom_ribbon(aes(ymin = low, ymax = high, fill = conditional)) +
  geom_line() +
  ylab('Conditional bobcat\noccupancy probability') +
  xlab('Latitude') +
  labs(fill = 'Coyote state') +
  theme(text = element_text(size = 25),
        legend.position = c(0.75, 0.85))

Conditional occupancy probability

cond_fig

Notice that when coyotes are present, there is a negative correlation with occupancy and latitude.

However, notice there is no relationship when coyotes are absent. This is consistent with our model for the bobcat \(1^{st}\) order natural parameter, which is conditional on absence of coyote (and all other species).

Marginal occupancy probability

  • Create a data.frame for predictions
  • Include complete range of observed disturbance; hold all other variables at their mean
nd_marg <- data.frame(
  Dist_5km = seq(min(occ_covs$Dist_5km), max(occ_covs$Dist_5km),
                 length.out = 100),
  HDens_5km = rep(mean(occ_covs$HDens_5km), 100),
  People_site = rep(mean(occ_covs$People_site), 100),
  Latitude = rep(mean(occ_covs$Latitude), 100)
)

Marginal occupancy probability

  • Omit the cond argument if you wish to calculate marginal occupancy probability
  • Averages over presence / absence of all other species
bob_marg <- predict(fit_3, type = 'state', species = 'bobcat',
                    newdata = nd_marg)
## Bootstrapping confidence intervals with 100 samples

gg_df_marg <- data.frame(

Breaking the model

A common mistake I see is for students to fit the biggest possible model right out of the gate. Lets see what this might look like:

fit_4 <- occuMulti(detformulas = c('~temp', '~temp', '~temp'),
                   stateformulas = c('~Dist_5km', '~HDens_5km', '~People_site',
                                     '~Latitude + Longitude',
                                     '~Latitude + Longitude',
                                     '~Latitude + Longitude'),
                   maxOrder = 2,
                   data = msom_data,
                   control = list(maxit = 1000))

Penalized likelihood

  • We can constrain such unreasonably large estimates by imposing a penalty on large values of a coefficient
  • Shrinks estimates toward 0
  • Imposes a small bias in return for a large reduction in variance
  • Will be available in next unmarked release. Available now via GitHub
  • Details in Clipp et al.2021

Penalized likelihood

  • Implemented penalized likelihood via optimizePenalty function
  • Requires a fitted model as input
  • Specify a range of penalties (bigger penalties = more shrinkage)
  • Uses cross-validation to identify optimal penalty, fits model the optimal penalty
# this is slow to run
opt_pen <- optimizePenalty(fit_4,
                            penalties = 2 ^ seq(-5, 5),
                            boot = 100)

The above function will take a while to run, and the resulting object is too big to store on GitHub. You can download the .rds file here:

Download opt_pen.rds

Continuous-time MSOM

  • Recent advances allow modeling of detection in continuous time
  • Permits simultaneous inference on spatial and temporal interactions
  • Not yet implemented in fancy software
  • Kellner et al.In press
